The paper applies evolutionary game theory to model the spectrum access problem in cognitive radio networks, which suggests that it may belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. The paper also proposes distributed spectrum access policies based on imitation, which involves interactions between multiple agents, indicating that it may also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the analysis of convergence properties and induced dynamics, which suggests that it may belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The paper also deals with decentralized adaptive learning environments, which suggests that it may belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the application of cognitive radios, which suggests that it may belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
